|publisher=OSCE|url=http://www.osce.org/documents/mc/2004/04/2783_en.pdf}}\n*{{cite web |title=The Status of the Croatian Serb Population in Bosnia and Herzegovina|year=|publisher=UNHCR|url=http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/pdfid/3eccfafc2.pdf}}\n*{{cite book |editor=Davidov, Dinko|title=War damage sustained by orthodox churches in Serbian areas of Croatia in 1991|publisher=Ministry of Information|location=Belgrade|year=1992}}\n*{{Cite web |title=Application of the Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide (Croatia v. Serbia) \u2013 Summary of the Judgment of 3 February 2015|url=https://www.icj-cij.org/files/case-related/118/18450.pdf |df=dmy-all|date=2015-02-03|publisher=International Court of Justice (ICJ)}}\n\n===News===\n*{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-31104973 |title=Court rejects Balkan genocide claims |language=en-GB |date=2015-02-03 |work=BBC News |df=dmy-all |accessdate=2018-12-30}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Serbs of Croatia}}\n* {{cite web|title=Prosvjeta|publisher=SKD \"Prosvjeta\"|url=http://prosvjeta.net/}}\n* [http://www.ffzg.unizg.hr/pov/zavod/triplex2/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/ROKSANDIC_srbi_u_hrvatskoj.pdf D. Roksandi\u0107, ''Srbi u Hrvatskoj \u2014 od 15. stolje\u0107a do dana\u0161njih dana'', Vjesnik, Zagreb 1991.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121013203451/http://www.rastko.org.rs/isk/images/chest_ador.html Tradition chest adornment worn in Kninska Krajina]\n* [http://www.dzs.hr/default_e.htm Croatian census 2001] (see \"Censuses\" at ''Crostat Database'')\n\n{{Ethnic groups in Croatia}}\n{{Serbian diaspora}}\n{{Serbian minority institutions and organizations in Croatia}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2011}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Serbs Of Croatia}}\n[[Category:Serbs of Croatia| ]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Croatia]]\n[[Category:History of the Serbs of Croatia| ]]\n[[Category:Serb minorities|Croatia]]\n[[Category:Serbian Orthodox Church in Croatia]]\n", "name_user": "Mikola22", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMedieval history", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serbs_of_Croatia"}
{"title_page": "Wendell Ladner", "text_new": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Wendell Ladner\n| image = Wendell Ladner 1975.jpeg\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1948|10|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Necaise Crossing, Mississippi]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1975|6|24|1948|10|6}}\n| death_place = [[Jamaica, New York]]\n| nationality = American\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 5\n| weight_lb = 220\n| high_school = [[Hancock North Central High School|Hancock North Central]]<br/>([[Kiln, Mississippi]])\n| college = [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles basketball|Southern Miss]] (1967\u20131970)\n| draft_year = 1970\n| career_start = 1970\n| career_end = 1975\n| career_position = [[Forward (basketball)|Forward]]\n| career_number = 33, 4\n| years1 = {{abay|1970|start}}\u2013{{abay|1971|end}}\n| team1 = [[Memphis Pros]]\n| years2 = {{abay|1971|end}}\n| team2 = [[Carolina Cougars]]\n| years3 = {{abay|1972|full=y}}\n| team3 = [[Memphis Tams]]\n| years4 = {{abay|1972|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1973|end}}\n| team4 = [[Kentucky Colonels]]\n| years5 = {{abay|1974|end}}\n| team5 = [[New York Nets]]\n| highlights = \n* [[ABA champion]] ([[1974 ABA Playoffs|1974]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[ABA All-Star]] ([[1971 ABA All-Star Game|1971]], [[1972 ABA All-Star Game|1972]])\n* [[ABA All-Rookie First Team]] ([[1970\u201371 ABA season|1971]])\n| stats_league = ABA\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 3,474 (11.6 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 2,481 (8.3 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value = 621 (2.1 apg)\n| bbr = ladnewe01\n}}\n'''Wendell Ladner''' (October 6, 1948 \u2013 June 24, 1975) was an American professional [[basketball]] player most notable for his time playing time in the [[American Basketball Association|ABA]] from 1970-1975.\n\nLadner was born in Necaise Crossing, [[Hancock County, Mississippi]] and played high school ball at Hancock North Central High School in [[Kiln, Mississippi]]. After attending the [[University of Southern Mississippi]], Ladner went undrafted in the 1970 ABA draft where he played five seasons with five different teams in the ABA, from [[1970\u201371 ABA season|1970]] to [[1974\u201375 ABA season|1975]]. A {{height|ft=6|in=5}} and {{convert|220|lb|kg}} [[forward (basketball)|forward]], Ladner was one of the great \"enforcers\" of the [[American Basketball Association]], protecting [[Dan Issel]] of the [[Kentucky Colonels]] and [[Julius Erving]] of the [[New York Nets]]. He was named to the 1971 ABA All-Rookie team. He was selected twice to the ABA all-star game, once in 1971 and second in 1972\n\nLadner died at the age of 26 in a June 24, 1975, crash of [[Eastern Air Lines Flight 66]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/2016/07/16/editor-column-plane-down-pro-athlete-dead-news-interest-stoked/86752164/|title=Editor column: Plane down, pro athlete dead, news interest stoked|website=The Poughkeepsie Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He was identified by medical examiners because he was wearing his ABA championship ring.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nelson|first1=John|title=Airplane Crash Claims Wndell Ladner's Life|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=266&dat=19750624&id=k2JhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1GgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1000,6146532&hl=en|accessdate=September 20, 2016|work=Kentucky New Era|agency=Associated Press|date=June 25, 1975|page=20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Chang|first1=Dean|title=A New Nets Era, but Much Has Been Left Behind|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/21/sports/basketball/one-fans-rocky-relationship-with-the-nets.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=September 20, 2016|date=April 20, 2013}}</ref> For many years, the Nets included his name and number in their list of retired numbers, though Ladner's no. 4 did not hang in the rafters with the other retired numbers. His number was also given to [[Rick Mahorn]] during his tenure with the Nets. In October 2013, a ''[[New York Daily News]]'' article explained that the number was never formally retired. However, out of respect to Ladner, Nets trainer Fritz Massmann had not issued No. 4 to other players for 17 years after Ladner's death.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bondy |first1=Stefan |title=SOLVED: The mysterious case of Wendell Ladner's (un)retired jersey |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/nets/solved-mysterious-case-wendell-ladner-retired-jersey-blog-entry-1.1633320 |website=nydailynews.com |accessdate=July 26, 2015 |date=October 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nErving called Ladner his wackiest teammate because he wanted to be [[Burt Reynolds]] with a basketball. ''[[Semi-Pro]]'', a basketball comedy set in the 1970s and starring [[Will Ferrell]], spoofs Ladner's Burt Reynolds persona in its trailer.\n\nLadner also has a road in [[Perkinston, Mississippi|Perkinston]],[[Mississippi]] named after him in his honor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Wendell+Ladner+Rd,+Mississippi+39573/@30.5941392,-89.43478,16z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x889db492e09e5481:0xef59c74e42227a06!8m2!3d30.5941392!4d-89.4304026|title=Wendell Ladner Rd|website=Wendell Ladner Rd|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*ABA statistics at [https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/l/ladnewe01.html Basketball Reference]\n*{{Find a Grave|11204646}}\n* Jim O'Brien: [http://www.remembertheaba.com/ABAArticles/OBrienArticleLadner.html ''Wendell Ladner'']\n\n{{New York Nets 1973\u201374 ABA champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ladner, Wendell}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Carolina Cougars players]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Colonels players]]\n[[Category:Memphis Pros players]]\n[[Category:Memphis Tams players]]\n[[Category:New York Nets players]]\n[[Category:People from Hancock County, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Southern Miss Golden Eagles basketball players]]\n[[Category:Victims of aviation accidents or incidents in the United States]]\n\n\n{{1940s-US-basketball-bio-stub}}\n[[Category:American Basketball Association players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Wendell Ladner\n| image = Wendell Ladner 1975.jpeg\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1948|10|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Necaise Crossing, Mississippi]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1975|6|24|1948|10|6}}\n| death_place = [[Jamaica, New York]]\n| nationality = American\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 5\n| weight_lb = 220\n| high_school = [[Hancock North Central High School|Hancock North Central]]<br/>([[Kiln, Mississippi]])\n| college = [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles basketball|Southern Miss]] (1967\u20131970)\n| draft_year = 1970\n| career_start = 1970\n| career_end = 1975\n| career_position = [[Forward (basketball)|Forward]]\n| career_number = 33, 4\n| years1 = {{abay|1970|start}}\u2013{{abay|1971|end}}\n| team1 = [[Memphis Pros]]\n| years2 = {{abay|1971|end}}\n| team2 = [[Carolina Cougars]]\n| years3 = {{abay|1972|full=y}}\n| team3 = [[Memphis Tams]]\n| years4 = {{abay|1972|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1973|end}}\n| team4 = [[Kentucky Colonels]]\n| years5 = {{abay|1974|end}}\n| team5 = [[New York Nets]]\n| highlights = \n* [[ABA champion]] ([[1974 ABA Playoffs|1974]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[ABA All-Star]] ([[1971 ABA All-Star Game|1971]], [[1972 ABA All-Star Game|1972]])\n* [[ABA All-Rookie First Team]] ([[1970\u201371 ABA season|1971]])\n| stats_league = ABA\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 3,474 (11.6 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 2,481 (8.3 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value = 621 (2.1 apg)\n| bbr = ladnewe01\n}}\n'''Wendell Ladner''' (October 6, 1948 \u2013 June 24, 1975) was an American professional [[basketball]] player most notable for his time playing time in the [[American Basketball Association|ABA]] from 1970-1975.\n\nLadner was born in Necaise Crossing, [[Hancock County, Mississippi]] and played high school ball at Hancock North Central High School in [[Kiln, Mississippi]]. After attending the [[University of Southern Mississippi]], Ladner went undrafted in the 1970 ABA draft where he played five seasons with five different teams in the ABA, from [[1970\u201371 ABA season|1970]] to [[1974\u201375 ABA season|1975]]. A {{height|ft=6|in=5}} and {{convert|220|lb|kg}} [[forward (basketball)|forward]], Ladner was one of the great \"enforcers\" of the [[American Basketball Association]], protecting [[Dan Issel]] of the [[Kentucky Colonels]] and [[Julius Erving]] of the [[New York Nets]]. He was named to the 1971 ABA All-Rookie team. He was selected twice to the ABA all-star game, once in 1971 and second in 1972\n\nLadner died at the age of 26 in a June 24, 1975, crash of [[Eastern Air Lines Flight 66]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/story/news/2016/07/16/editor-column-plane-down-pro-athlete-dead-news-interest-stoked/86752164/|title=Editor column: Plane down, pro athlete dead, news interest stoked|website=The Poughkeepsie Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He was identified by medical examiners because he was wearing his ABA championship ring.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nelson|first1=John|title=Airplane Crash Claims Wndell Ladner's Life|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=266&dat=19750624&id=k2JhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1GgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1000,6146532&hl=en|accessdate=September 20, 2016|work=Kentucky New Era|agency=Associated Press|date=June 25, 1975|page=20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Chang|first1=Dean|title=A New Nets Era, but Much Has Been Left Behind|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/21/sports/basketball/one-fans-rocky-relationship-with-the-nets.html|website=The New York Times|accessdate=September 20, 2016|date=April 20, 2013}}</ref> For many years, the Nets included his name and number in their list of retired numbers, though Ladner's no. 4 did not hang in the rafters with the other retired numbers. His number was also given to [[Rick Mahorn]] during his tenure with the Nets. In October 2013, a ''[[New York Daily News]]'' article explained that the number was never formally retired. However, out of respect to Ladner, Nets trainer Fritz Massmann had not issued No. 4 to other players for 17 years after Ladner's death.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bondy |first1=Stefan |title=SOLVED: The mysterious case of Wendell Ladner's (un)retired jersey |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/nets/solved-mysterious-case-wendell-ladner-retired-jersey-blog-entry-1.1633320 |website=nydailynews.com |accessdate=July 26, 2015 |date=October 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nErving called Ladner his wackiest teammate because he wanted to be [[Burt Reynolds]] with a basketball. ''[[Semi-Pro]]'', a basketball comedy set in the 1970s and starring [[Will Ferrell]], spoofs Ladner's Burt Reynolds persona in its trailer.\n\nLadner also has a road in [[Perkinston, Mississippi|Perkinston]],[[Mississippi]] named after him in his honor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Wendell+Ladner+Rd,+Mississippi+39573/@30.5941392,-89.43478,16z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x889db492e09e5481:0xef59c74e42227a06!8m2!3d30.5941392!4d-89.4304026|title=Wendell Ladner Rd|website=Wendell Ladner Rd|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*ABA statistics at [https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/l/ladnewe01.html Basketball Reference]\n*{{Find a Grave|11204646}}\n* Jim O'Brien: [http://www.remembertheaba.com/ABAArticles/OBrienArticleLadner.html ''Wendell Ladner'']\n\n{{New York Nets 1973\u201374 ABA champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ladner, Wendell}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Carolina Cougars players]]\n[[